Some crosstalk simulations

Click here for the simulations of a longer baseline ("skipping" a dish).

Click here for the simulations of a dish with a rolled rim.

Unless otherwise indicated, the following simulations were performed with the "large" feed that has a flat ~50-60% efficiency across the band.
This feed sticks out exactly 218 mm (this is the position at which it reaches that good efficiency).

Crosstalks within the feed alone

I created a separate page to focus on the "in dish" crosstalks, since they constitute a separate problem. The "in dish" crosstalks are the ones from one polarization to the other, within the same dish, and happen mostly because of the presence of a balun. In the page you're currently reading, I focus on the crosstalk between two dishes.

Here is the setup of the two dishes, with the polarizations and corresponding port numbers.

Here is the simplest simulation: feeds are positioned with phase center at focus (so they stick out 218 mm), the dishes are 6 m dishes with focal ratio 0.25, and there are no fences or other modification. The feed rim-to-rim distance is 40 cm (which corresponds to 640 center-to-center, but I will cite numbers in rim-to-rim).

Increasing the distance between dishes

In the simulation above, and unless otherwise specified, all simulations are performed with a 40 cm rim-to-rim distance. Let's look at what different dish distances might produce.

Note that I will only present the S3,1's. Since I worry about the dish-to-dish crosstalk, I will not use baluns, and so I will not present S2,1's. I will also not show the S4,2's since they are significiantly lower than the S3,1's and there is no reason why increasing the dish distance would increase the S4,2's. For these reasons, I also don't present the S4,1's.

Increasing the dish distance does not make a large difference.

Adding a fence

The second idea is to add a fence around the rim of the dish:

I simulated different fence heights, here they are, for a constant 40 cm distance:

The fence does decrease the crosstalks, but it has to be large (>50 cm) to beat down the crosstalks by 10 dB.

Making the dishes deeper

Another way of mitigating the crosstalks is to make the dishes deeper, i.e. the focus would now be below the rim of the dish.

I simulated two different ways of doing that: fixing the position of the focus and extending the diameter, or fixing the diameter and lowering the focus. See the diagram below for comparisons.

Fixing the position of the focus

For a 6 m dish with an f/D=0.25, the focus is 1.5 m from the bottom, which is also the "depth" (=height of the rim) of the dish. We can make the dish deeper by fixing the focus at 1.5 m, but extending the diameter so that the dish gets deeper. I chose the "extra depth" to be the independent variable, and I simulated 10, 20, 40, and 80 cm extra depths. Here are the corresponding dish properties:

Extra depth (mm) Total depth (mm) Corresponding diameter (mm) Corresponding focal ratio
0 1500 6000 0.25
100 1600 6197 0.242
200 1700 6387 0.235
400 1900 6753 0.222
800 2300 7430 0.202

Here are the results, for a constant 40 cm dish distance:

Hence we see that larger, deeper dishes reduce crosstalk by a significant amount, but the dishes are significantly larger, too.

Fixing the diameter

The other way I tried deepening the dishes was by fixing the diameter and decreasing the focal ratio. Again, I used the extra depth as the independent variable.

Here are the parameters I simulated:

Extra depth (mm) Total depth (mm) Corresponding focal ratio
0 1500 0.25
200 1700 0.234
300 1800 0.226
400 1900 0.219
500 2000 0.212
600 2100 0.205

Note that I did not add as much depth in this setup because I was trying to maintain the focal ratio above 0.2. My reasoning is that anything below that would be too far from the original shape for which the feed is optimized, and the efficiencies would tank.

Here are the results:

Simulations at 45 degrees

Since the S4,2 crosstalk is roughly 20 dB lower than the S3,1, this suggests that the angle between a polarization plane and the dish translation vector is a significant variable. I simulated the following setup:

Note that in this setup, the feed legs need to be rotate 45 degrees too, which may not be desirable from a mechanical standpoint.

In this case, thanks to symmetry, I really only need to excite one port. Here are the results, for a fixed 40 cm dish distance, compared to the non-rotated (0 deg) case:

Things to notice:

  1. The S3,1 45 deg (equivalent to S4,2 in the 45 degrees case, which I didn't simulate) is lower than the S3,1 of the 0 degrees case by about 10 dB in the low frequency range, but is 10 dB higher than the S4,2 of the 0 degrees case,
  2. The S4,1 45 deg is as large as the S3,1,
  3. The 45 degree cross-dish crosstalks have a bump around 1 GHz.

Combining some of these attempts

To understand how some of these methods add up, I simulated different combinations.

Adding a fence to the 45-degree-rotated simulations

I added fences of different heights to 45-degree-rotated simulations, at a constant 40 cm separation.

Adding a fence to a deeper dish (fixed diameter)

I added fences of different heights to simulations with a deeper dish (300 mm deeper, fixed diameter), at a constant 40 cm separation.

It seems like the fence don't help much. My suspicion: if the feed is already fully hidden, adding a fence will just worsen the diffraction.

Changing the distance of deeper dishes (fixed diameter)

I changed the dish separation of simulations with a deeper dish (300 mm deeper, fixed diameter).

The behaviour is the same as with a regular (not deeper) dish.
